  "prompt": "Is it a fact that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, it is a fact that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. It is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Similar laws exist in other countries, such as the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002** in the United Kingdom and the **Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA)** in India. Additionally, international organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to combat money laundering globally.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture, depending on the severity of the offense and the jurisdiction.",
